detail.content: Fall 2015 Schedule    | German | NYU                                                                                                                                                     Back to Previous Page         Fall 2015 Schedule      Fall  2015 Schedule     GERM-UA111  T,  R 11:00 – 12:15   Conversation  and Composition: Berlin in Motion   Doreen  Densky   Conversation and  Composition is designed for post-intermediate students of German with a solid  grasp of German grammar and vocabulary who wish to expand on their knowledge of  the German language, history, and culture through reading, discussion, and  writing. Conversation and Composition is a reading, writing, and speaking  intensive course. Emphasis will be placed on refining written and spoken  expression, with particular focus on the ability to articulate opinions,  exchange substantive information, and argue points of view; developing analytic  and interpretive writing skills; and encouraging flexibility of expression. In  addition, a thorough grammar review will be part of our work.  This course explores  Berlin as a metropolis in constant flux. Place of rapid industrialization,  fertile ground for cultural experimentation in the Weimar Republic, site of  rubble after the Third Reich ’s  fall ,  divided city during the Cold War, capital of reunified Germany, magnet for  artists and hub for cultural diversity today: Berlin’s energy derives from its  continuous readjustments. We will study a variety of texts (poetry, narrative  prose, journalistic writing) and visual media (painting, photography, film) to  discuss Berlin’s culture and trace its turbulent history from around 1900 to  the present.    Conducted in German.      GERM-UA153  T,  R 12:30 – 1:45  Techniques  of Translation    Andrea  Dortmann     This course  introduces students to the history, theory, and practice of translation through  German and English texts taken from a variety of cultural backgrounds. While  engaging in the craft of translation first hand, students will encounter  diverse contrastive grammatical, syntactical, and stylistic problems, thus  gaining a deeper understanding of the German language. The course also stresses  the acquisition of vocabulary and complex idiomatic structures necessary for  effective reading comprehension as well as written expression. A background  reader in English will familiarize students with historical and theoretical  implications of translation.  Photocopies of  primary texts in German (and English) to be translated will be distributed by  the instructor. Materials may include newspaper and magazine articles; recipes;  TV- and print advertisements; scientific and philosophical articles; pop  material such as hip hop and rap songs, cartoons; Literary texts: prose,  theater, poetry, libretti, among others. In addition to those weekly  translation assignments, which will be critically assessed in class, we will  translate one or more longer prose texts (TBD) from German to English as a  class. This work will accompany our course throughout the semester. Conducted in German.    GERM-UA253   T,  R 3:30 - 4:45   Man, Monster, Machine: A Century of German Film  (Topics in German Cinema)   Doreen  Densky     This course presents  a survey of German cinema with an emphasis on questions of how the filmic  medium depicts human life and pushes the boundaries of body and psyche. We will  begin by tracing the reappearance of uncanny figures inherited from Romantic  storytelling (supernatural beings, undead, robots) in classics of Weimar film.  We will then look at how a superhuman gaze is staged in Nazi propaganda cinema;  how ordinary life and the status of the outsider are explored by filmmakers in  both parts of the divided Germany; and how Post-Wall film continues to  negotiate private and public identities, life and technology, games and  psychology. In addition to discussing the complex history of authoritarianism,  prejudice, persecution, and surveillance alongside of selected movies and  critical readings, we will analyze the narrative and dramatic development in  individual films as well as elements of form and style. Our viewings will include  works by filmmakers such as Paul Wegener, F.W. Murnau, Fritz Lang, Leni  Riefenstahl, Konrad Wolf, Volker Schlöndorff, Margarethe von Trotta, Werner  Herzog, Rainer Werner Fassbinder, Michael Haneke, Oliver Hirschbiegel, Florian  Henckel von Donnersmarck, and Christian Petzold . Taught in English.     GERM-UA283  W  3:30 - 6:00  Doppelgänger:  Figures of Multiple Identity (Topics)    Rosemarie  Brucher      This course focuses  on aesthetic explorations of figures of multiple identity in literature,  theatre, and film from the 18th century to the present. We will investigate the  ways in which processes of identity disintegration are dealt with in terms of  both content and form. In addition to artistic explorations of the multiple, we  will study key philosophical concepts of disintegration and psychological  approaches to this theme. Central questions include: What does it mean to  conceive of identity as structurally multiple, devoid of its integrative  function? What are the key characteristics of such a multiple identity? Do  artistic explorations of the multiple help us to identify and investigate  alternative modes of consciousness? Does such a radical concept of identity  affect aesthetic processes? What are the potentials and limits of various art  forms and their respective tools in these artistic explorations? And, finally,  what does the disintegration of the ego mean for symbolic/discursive,  psychosocial, and socio-historical processes? Selected authors/artists will be  among others: Heinrich von Kleist, Annette von Droste-Hülshoff, Robert Louis  Stevenson, Fyodor Dostoyevsky, E.T.A. Hoffmann, Friedrich Nietzsche, Sigmund  Freud, Ernst Mach, Ann Liv Young, Matt Ruff, Joyce Carol Oates, Cindy Sherman, Alejandro Jodorowsky,  and Elfriede Jelinek. Taught in English .    GERM-UA369  M,  W 11:00 - 12:15  Post-1945  Austrian Literature    Rosemarie  Brucher     This  course introduces you to the most representative authors and  exemplary literary texts from Austria after 1945. Covering  the three major literary genres – poetry, prose, drama – the course examines characteristics of postwar Austrian  literature by looking at questions of form and narrativity . Such questions are, e.g., the crisis of language and  representation; the critique of the role and self-positioning of Austria in and  after World War II; the dominance of Catholicism in postwar Austria; and the  intentional destruction of beauty in a country whose national anthem celebrates  Austria as a “nation graced with beauty.” Selected authors will include:  Ingeborg Bachmann, Thomas Bernhard, Elfriede Jelinek, die Wiener Gruppe, Werner  Schwab, Elfriede Gerstl, Wolfgang Bauer, and Friederike Mayröcker. Taught in  German . Fall 2015 Schedule    | German | NYU                                                                                                                                                     Back to Previous Page         Fall 2015 Schedule      Fall  2015 Schedule     GERM-UA111  T,  R 11:00 – 12:15   Conversation  and Composition: Berlin in Motion   Doreen  Densky   Conversation and  Composition is designed for post-intermediate students of German with a solid  grasp of German grammar and vocabulary who wish to expand on their knowledge of  the German language, history, and culture through reading, discussion, and  writing. Conversation and Composition is a reading, writing, and speaking  intensive course. Emphasis will be placed on refining written and spoken  expression, with particular focus on the ability to articulate opinions,  exchange substantive information, and argue points of view; developing analytic  and interpretive writing skills; and encouraging flexibility of expression. In  addition, a thorough grammar review will be part of our work.  This course explores  Berlin as a metropolis in constant flux. Place of rapid industrialization,  fertile ground for cultural experimentation in the Weimar Republic, site of  rubble after the Third Reich ’s  fall ,  divided city during the Cold War, capital of reunified Germany, magnet for  artists and hub for cultural diversity today: Berlin’s energy derives from its  continuous readjustments. We will study a variety of texts (poetry, narrative  prose, journalistic writing) and visual media (painting, photography, film) to  discuss Berlin’s culture and trace its turbulent history from around 1900 to  the present.    Conducted in German.      GERM-UA153  T,  R 12:30 – 1:45  Techniques  of Translation    Andrea  Dortmann     This course  introduces students to the history, theory, and practice of translation through  German and English texts taken from a variety of cultural backgrounds. While  engaging in the craft of translation first hand, students will encounter  diverse contrastive grammatical, syntactical, and stylistic problems, thus  gaining a deeper understanding of the German language. The course also stresses  the acquisition of vocabulary and complex idiomatic structures necessary for  effective reading comprehension as well as written expression. A background  reader in English will familiarize students with historical and theoretical  implications of translation.  Photocopies of  primary texts in German (and English) to be translated will be distributed by  the instructor. Materials may include newspaper and magazine articles; recipes;  TV- and print advertisements; scientific and philosophical articles; pop  material such as hip hop and rap songs, cartoons; Literary texts: prose,  theater, poetry, libretti, among others. In addition to those weekly  translation assignments, which will be critically assessed in class, we will  translate one or more longer prose texts (TBD) from German to English as a  class. This work will accompany our course throughout the semester. Conducted in German.    GERM-UA253   T,  R 3:30 - 4:45   Man, Monster, Machine: A Century of German Film  (Topics in German Cinema)   Doreen  Densky     This course presents  a survey of German cinema with an emphasis on questions of how the filmic  medium depicts human life and pushes the boundaries of body and psyche. We will  begin by tracing the reappearance of uncanny figures inherited from Romantic  storytelling (supernatural beings, undead, robots) in classics of Weimar film.  We will then look at how a superhuman gaze is staged in Nazi propaganda cinema;  how ordinary life and the status of the outsider are explored by filmmakers in  both parts of the divided Germany; and how Post-Wall film continues to  negotiate private and public identities, life and technology, games and  psychology. In addition to discussing the complex history of authoritarianism,  prejudice, persecution, and surveillance alongside of selected movies and  critical readings, we will analyze the narrative and dramatic development in  individual films as well as elements of form and style. Our viewings will include  works by filmmakers such as Paul Wegener, F.W. Murnau, Fritz Lang, Leni  Riefenstahl, Konrad Wolf, Volker Schlöndorff, Margarethe von Trotta, Werner  Herzog, Rainer Werner Fassbinder, Michael Haneke, Oliver Hirschbiegel, Florian  Henckel von Donnersmarck, and Christian Petzold . Taught in English.     GERM-UA283  W  3:30 - 6:00  Doppelgänger:  Figures of Multiple Identity (Topics)    Rosemarie  Brucher      This course focuses  on aesthetic explorations of figures of multiple identity in literature,  theatre, and film from the 18th century to the present. We will investigate the  ways in which processes of identity disintegration are dealt with in terms of  both content and form. In addition to artistic explorations of the multiple, we  will study key philosophical concepts of disintegration and psychological  approaches to this theme. Central questions include: What does it mean to  conceive of identity as structurally multiple, devoid of its integrative  function? What are the key characteristics of such a multiple identity? Do  artistic explorations of the multiple help us to identify and investigate  alternative modes of consciousness? Does such a radical concept of identity  affect aesthetic processes? What are the potentials and limits of various art  forms and their respective tools in these artistic explorations? And, finally,  what does the disintegration of the ego mean for symbolic/discursive,  psychosocial, and socio-historical processes? Selected authors/artists will be  among others: Heinrich von Kleist, Annette von Droste-Hülshoff, Robert Louis  Stevenson, Fyodor Dostoyevsky, E.T.A. Hoffmann, Friedrich Nietzsche, Sigmund  Freud, Ernst Mach, Ann Liv Young, Matt Ruff, Joyce Carol Oates, Cindy Sherman, Alejandro Jodorowsky,  and Elfriede Jelinek. Taught in English .    GERM-UA369  M,  W 11:00 - 12:15  Post-1945  Austrian Literature    Rosemarie  Brucher     This  course introduces you to the most representative authors and  exemplary literary texts from Austria after 1945. Covering  the three major literary genres – poetry, prose, drama – the course examines characteristics of postwar Austrian  literature by looking at questions of form and narrativity . Such questions are, e.g., the crisis of language and  representation; the critique of the role and self-positioning of Austria in and  after World War II; the dominance of Catholicism in postwar Austria; and the  intentional destruction of beauty in a country whose national anthem celebrates  Austria as a “nation graced with beauty.” Selected authors will include:  Ingeborg Bachmann, Thomas Bernhard, Elfriede Jelinek, die Wiener Gruppe, Werner  Schwab, Elfriede Gerstl, Wolfgang Bauer, and Friederike Mayröcker. Taught in  German .
